<subSubSection pageId="29" pageNumber="28" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="29.[192,1440,1340,1401]" pageId="29" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,324,1341,1367]" pageId="29" pageNumber="28">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Opitz" authorityYear="2020" box="[561,651,1341,1366]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Axina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="piperata">
<emphasis box="[561,651,1341,1366]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="28">piperata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is a Latin name that stems from 
<emphasis box="[1028,1084,1341,1366]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="28">piper</emphasis>
(= pepper). I refer to the sprinkled-like appearance of the brown elytral asetiferous punctures.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
